76561197970925803,Recommended,324260,16007543,"Posted: 25 May, 2015",all,Dagit,"Good:Relatively inexpensive game.Fun combat.Great visuals.Good RPG elements.Good autosave.Good replayability. I beat it three times and I think there is still at least one ending I haven't seen.Supports mods.Bad:Crashes to desktop for me about one in three hours of play or so, not a huge issue because it saves frequently.The story telling overall is weak, even though quests often have interesting options.Combat appears hard at first, but late in the game it's too easy if you power up everything and fly the best ship.If you are fan of games like Escape Velocity or SPAZ then you need to play this."
76561198006595204,Not Recommended,324260,15238183,"Posted: 6 April, 2015",all,Sikareus,"At the risk of sounding a litle too ""me too!"" I feel obligated to weigh in on this game. It has the potential to be great, and I love the art style and mimalistic UI, but it doesn't have enough rich content yet. If you read no further, wishlist this title and check on it from time to time. I don't think my ""no"" will stick forever.For those of you with longer attention spans, I'll expound a bit. VoidExpanse is the type of game I'm really wanting to sink my teeth into, but can't. Similiar titles in the genre include things like Spaz and Drox Operative (definitely check both of those out for similiar (but different) experiences. VoidExpanse gives you a nice-looking sandbox to play in, but doesn't give you all the toys necessary to have a good time. The skeleton is all here, but the experience feels empty a few hours in.There simply isn't enough breadth/depth to what you can do to (or with) your character. The classes and ship options are fairly one-dimensional, and the quests are still pretty rinse and repeat. I'd love to see more dynamic quests involving attacks on space stations, some kind of hacking interface/skill tree, true smuggling runs, more interaction (even the ability to join) with the pirate faction, etc. The game just doesn't do interesting things with it's own universe yet.I love this game for what it is, and for the price point I'm still happy with my purchase, I'm just hoping that they take this brilliant foundation and build something atop it. I know there are countless ideas floating around the community - let's hope some of them see the light of day."
,Not Recommended,324260,23530810,"Posted: 12 June, 2016",all,Master Beta Tester,"I loved this game. Although others weren't, I was impressed witht eh graphics, and overall story options. They even include free deicated server software. Each of those features is great.However, unknown to me, or my friends, the multiplayer is NOT I bought a four pack to play this game with my friends, which we did and enjoyed every second, until it abruptly ended. Not even four quests in, the game tells us that we've reached the end of the possible multiplayer quest and can continue the game in single player to experience the rest of the story. What? This is a multiplayer game, but only a percentage of the game can be played in multiplayer mode? And it's not like I can transfer my character to a single player game, each server/game is a fresh start.Overall, I'm incredibly disappointed with the game. Yet another unfinished piece of work released and advertised as a full game. For shame."
,Not Recommended,324260,15262642,"Posted: 8 April, 2015",all,Riolis,"Great combat, but suffer a massive downfall of a lack of content. Most of the playtime is used mostly travelling between space station. The content is lacking massively and the quest is excruciating painful to play and boring.I don't see the point of randomly generated world where there is barely anything you can do in it. You can destroy a pirate station but it doesn't effect anything in the game world, like making it safer and such. The faction doesn't grow or decrease in size with your interaction. You can't help your faction to setup new station nor they can be destroyed. Faction NPC do nothing but sit in station and just give a scripted quest (just ONE quest then they are useless forever). The astroid is static and doesnt move or dissapear when you mine. NPC pirates randomly added into the world but just stay there or chasing an npc freighter and then return to their spawn point and stay there indefinately.Trading is badly simulated as there is NO production station and NO demand station. Just the station price just change randomly change without making any sense. If you go to the capital system with 3 station you can make 200k+ just by trading between those station. There is no point to travel to the fringe station where you expect the demand is higher, but its not, everything is same price with the station you were on. Its just pointless RNG. (~_~)This ""Meaningful trading system involving trade routes and supply/demand simulation"" is a lie. sad face. I was really looking forward for this.In short, the world is dead, cold and pointless, with very few interaction. Nothing much to do but to follow the boring fetch quest. Great tech demo, but very far from a complete game like space ranger or SPAZ.I like the combat tho."
,Recommended,324260,15436027,"Posted: 18 April, 2015",all,Ichy 42,"I can't really speak to multiplayer as I haven't gotten into it yet but my solo experience thus far has been a lot of fun.I started out as a fighter, I knew that combat was going to be prevalent no matter where I went so I wanted a little head start in that department. After taking a good look at the skill trees I decided that I actually wanted most if not all of them so throughout my playtime I have been carefully managing what I invest in next. The game can be a little grindy, especially if you've *chosen* to grind as I have, but it's always felt rewarding. Getting that next skill, being able to buy and then use that shiny new hull or weapon or ship upgrade is satisfying.A lot of zones unfortunately feel a little empty. Filled to the brim with pirates and aliens and in some cases more asteroids than you can mine in half a day, yes, but still empty as from a certain standpoint they're essentially just waypoints to your next stop. Hopefully in the (near) future we'll have more interactivity with these places if the game evolves to a point where we can actually claim and populate them. Extended main storylines to send you to more places would be great, too. All the same, if you're in need of exp or loot to sell it's easy to just pick a zone whose agression level is close to yours and have at it.Storywise it's pretty solid. You'll have access to a few missions to raise your rep with three of the factions before you actually join any of them. The main quest for the two I've seen are pretty short but well written and the difficulty in terms of how aggressive the zones you'll be visiting is pretty steep so your first playthrough with a new character will feel a lot longer as you level and gear up. There are also missions you can do for the commander at any station you visit. They're selected randomly from a preset list and it's totally up to you if you want to accept them or not. I found that fact to be irritating as I was only really interested in bounty and mining missions, thankfully loudent2 published a mod that allows you access to the whole list so you can just pick the one you want. Much more convenient and a must if you ever get frustrated at the random factor.There are a lot of items and upgrades to choose from at the beginning, which is awesome, but as you get into the higher levels (I was 146 at the time of writing this... yes I was lazy and copy/pasted my three day old forum post. Deal with it :P) you'll find yourself invariably with the same set of gear as most people; primarily speaking a dark matter generator, a dimensional fuel tank, and either a Hammer or a Death Bringer hull. And lasers. Lots of love for the lasers :).This is where modding really adds more life to it all. Last week I wanted a (much) shorter range laser that did more damage, I made one. It uses way too much energy imo but I made it, I use it, and so do a few other people now that it's on the Workshop. Then I wanted a rapid fire ballistic weapon that shoots fireballs, made that too. It's a little OP for anything under aggression level 70 or so but it's fun all the same. Got tired of shields, made new armor plating. So my modding skills are amateurish at best but more importantly I'm having a good time doing it, even learned a thing or two about XML along the way. Taking that into consideration, there are a lot of other people writing fantastic mods for the game and publishing them fairly regularly, it's been just over two weeks and there are 50 items in the Workshop already (albeit some of them are translations and don't really affect the core gameplay but I imagine they took a LOT of work and it's quite appreciated to a lot of players). It feels like there's always some cool new user made content to check out and maybe take for a spin. Maybe even share a few of your own ;).All in all it's a great game. Simple yet very well written, looks fantastic, controls are solid, great support and frequent updates. It has a lot to offer both in terms of content and expandability and it's a lot of fun, right to the point where I started playing one morning and actually forgot to eat anything until mid afternoon. Definitely worth the pricepoint.Can I click yes twice?"
,Not Recommended,324260,15344127,"Posted: 13 April, 2015",all,Evan,"It's a work in progress. It has a lot of potential, but it should really be an early access title.It's definitely playable now, but pretty much everything needs either more work or more content. Load times for save games and new systems are pretty long. Combat is really repetitive (and you'll get used to it because it's the only sane way to level up). There are few options for ship and weapon, there are quite a few but generally only one at any given tier so it's ""oh I can afford the next ship/gun up I better swap them out."" Modders are adding content faster than the devs, but the devs set up modding so that once you use a save file with any mod it permenantly needs that mod to load, there is no removing it if say you don't like it or it completely breaks the game. Back up your save files.I was a die hard fan of the Escape Velocity games when I was younger and I really wanted a worthy successor to them in this game, but although many of the same elements are there pretty much all the things the EV series did right this title fails at. There's no real feeling of exploration because the procedurally generated systems are all identical other than color scheme and number/strength of bad guys. The storyline missions are uninspired and linear. And there aren't enough options in ships and outfits to make it feel like an inhabited capitalistic universe.I have hopes that enough of the rough patches will get ironed out as further patches come out that I feel like my money was well spent, but I'm not going to keep playing it while they fix it, and I can't recommend that you do either."
76561197970635329,Recommended,324260,32415883,Posted: 14 June,all,Wegadin,"This is a highly underated game, and if anyone is on the fence regarding it, I would highly encourage you to buy it.  Ship controls are similar to S.P.A.Z, which makes control of your ship very easy and intuitive.-Mining is also fun, enjoyablable, and relaxing.-The skill tree is great.  You have to really choose what skills you want, as even when you are level 55, you will not have evertyhing you want.  This is a good thing, as you will have to choose wisely as to what you want to be.  You can progress beyond that level, but it just takes a little more grinding (for a hefty fee, you can ""wipe your memory"" at a science station to try out new skills).-3 weapons types- Lasers, ballistics, and missles.  Each field is very unique with its own progression and tiers.-dozens of ships, and with the inclusion of the expansion, you get a battleship after completing the Pariah campaign.-Sector control, as you liberate systems from alien-infested hives.-trading-bounty, courier, mining, and trade missions from starbases.-customize your ship with different shields, engines, armor, boosting components, weapons, tools such as mining gear or EMP's, etc.This was a very enjoyable experience for me, and I am extremely glad I bought it."
