,Not Recommended,324260,15212322,"Posted: 4 April, 2015",all,Sha|)ini0,"The basics are there but this project is still in its alpha stages at best.Pros:-Interesting concept (sort of like a more real-time FTL with ARPG-like elements)-Attractive graphics and music-Game works well within the 1st 25 levelsCons:-After a few hours in (or beyond level 25), you realize that the game has offered everything it possibly can-Progress suddenly becomes repetitive and any updates are really shallow-Lots of random crashes for a ""finished product"" and issues with reloading your last save.-I found myself playing mobile games while I waited for my ship to make the many jumps from system to system (sometimes, you have to make as many as 13 jumps which can take up to 10 mins even with a highly-advanced ship)-Wonky auto-pilot and path-finding algorithm that ends up killing you almost 50% of the time-And when the auto-pilot kills you, you're teleported back to the very beginning of your path so you end up spending another 10 mins playing a mobile game!-Poor combat system that I bet sounded good on paper. For good strategic combat, you're better off with FTL. If you end up playing as a trader or miner, be prepared for BORING REPETITION!-Can't really see any replayability since most quests are procedurally generated and different character archetypes don't really mean anything except for the 1st few hours of gameplay.It's an OK game for its price tag but it's got a long way ahead of it before it becomes as immersive and addictive as some other similar titles out there. Here's hoping the devs can iron out some of the kinks and spend some time crafting some more varied missions."
,Not Recommended,324260,29937210,Posted: 15 February,all,Wazat1,"Overall: Hesitant dislike.  Kinda fun, kinda meh, lots of grinding, very empty; overall lands on the negative end, if only barely.It's a somewhat fun game, but spread too thin.  In the end I had some fun, but many game sessions felt unwholesome because of all the padding and time-wasting that diluted the experience.  It's also begging for content, so I'd recommend checking out lots of mods to enrich the experience; I now regret playing the game in its original form.TL;DR: It's kinda fun, but a very thin and grindy experience.  If you're looking for a time waster, it'll be fine for that; if not, it will feel very frustratingly slow and underwhelming.  I still feel an awful, kinda gross, unsatisfied sensation, even after beating it.  Like the time was very poorly spent.  :(  So keep that in mind when considering a purchase!There's very little story, and very few actual missions beyond the random ones the base leaders give you (and those are insubstantial).  Most of your time is spent traveling, whether on unsatisfying fetch or delivery quests, or traveling across half the galaxy to reach your quest again after a death.  The last few quests I did had a ton of travel from one corner of the galaxy to the other; very boring, even in the alien areas where the enemies were actually dangerous.  I did a medium sized galaxy and I recommend you try a small, simply to drop that travel time padding.Combat is somewhat fun, but it does feel awkward.  You're fighting foes who have the computer's good aim, but you need to aim manually and this makes many of the weapons awkward and impractical to use.  You need to figure out how to move with your weapon to land even a fraction of the hits, and enemies don't appear to be limited in ammo like you are.  I also figured out early on that energy weapons are the way to go -- instead of a limit of 20 shots, you turn your entire fuel tank into ammo, and you just need a powerful generator to keep your energy levels stocked.  If I remember right, for solid ammo, the game is extremely stingy with refill items for some reason, so you'll have to return to base constantly to stock up again; this is bad for longer missions, mining ventures, etc.The skill tree is almost entirely made of tiny stat upgrades, making you turn or strafe or cruise slightly faster, or do slightly more damage with a weapon type.  A few skills unlock better equipment, and one skill (persuade) adds dialog options in quests, and the rest are tiny, incremental stat boosts; very sterile.  For that reason the skill tree feels very unexciting... yes you make your ship work better, but with my level in the 60s it was only about 25-50% better in a select few areas.  And I had to focus in those areas to do it.  The game begs for that tree to be stuffed with new abilities in combat, mining, and quests, differences in *kind* instead of just differences in scale.Also it's a little frustrating that the starting classes are not even -- some simply have way more free skill points assigned at the start of the game.  You should play the class that has the most skills you like, but also the most skills total that you plan on taking... and that means doing some google searching.That's one example of how the game feels like it lacks balance, polish, and content.Did I enjoy it?  Yea, it wasokay.  But man was it a slow grind, and I feel like a different game might have done a better job.  I walked away from this game multiple times because I felt crappy after playing it, because the experience had been so grindy and empty.  It's an awful feeling.What's impressive is the good parts were just good enough to leave me nostalgic, and I returned to finish the story.  It actually feels like they were planning a bigger game, ran out of time/budget, released what they had with plans for later expansions, but then had to abandon it when the negative reviews rolled in.  And that's tragic, because there's a lot of potential here, but overall the experience is diluted, grindy, and unsatisfying.  :(Last of all, multiplayer: I played briefly with friends, but we drifted away from the game because if felt so empty, and didn't lend itself to non-combat playstyles.  Players who primarily wanted to trade or mine, for example, felt very disused.  I hear the game cuts you off after a few missions (you can only continue in single player), but we didn't get that far, so I can't say whether that's still the case.  Maybe worth a look, especially with mods?"
