76561198237577814,Recommended,324260,22261444,"Posted: 5 April, 2016",all,davidalangay,"I've played this game for like 10 hours now the first day I purchased it. Clearly I must like it.You have a good reason to like it too. This game reminds me of EVE Online only in an arcade format. There is a single player mode and a multiplayer mode.In this game you are a space adventurer struggling to deal with the aftermath of a disasterous war where your part of space is cut of after the Federation (no relation to Star Trek) destroys a stargate leading back to the heart of intersteller civilization, surrounded by a scant number of merchants, fellow stranded space adventurers, and aliens and pirates who want to kill you.This is a sandbox game. Yes you are given quests to do to earn currency, but you get to do what you want. You buy better ships for combat, exploration and mining, making sure you got the best weapons and devices snapped on. You loot destroyed enemies, or you get looted if they destroy you. There are three play modes, the first one (I'm familiar with) is you respawn after you die but you lose your loot. The last one is permadeath where you really do need balls of iron, because when you die, you die.You get to play in a faction, each one has advantages. There are six if memory serves. The single player mode stores a galaxy you can set the size of with a slider. I haven't tried multiplayer only because I just got the game. When I play multiplayer, I'll update my review.  Even if I hate multiplayer it won't change my recommendation because the single player mode is worth the money paid alone, with or without the discount.The ships you get to play range from small fighters to large warships but they cost money and, if you are an EVE Online player like me, you really need to fly only what you can afford to lose. While the hulls are limited to what you can slap on for hardpoints, there is room for some customization at the device part and some hardpoints allow either a beam or a ballistic weapon.You get to customize your character you play, gender, hairstyle, skin color, eye type, nose type, mouth type, accessory...it's limited but I'm sure the devs will add more choices...yes, that was a hint.There's a class and skill tree where you can tailor your character's development as the character earns levels. You get to choose a class, miner, combat, etc, with some of the basic skill points aready filled on, and then as you level you earn skill points where you can allocate to parts of the skill tree, like efficiency in energy usage for firing weapons and shield operation, or tracking weapon turret time. If you played EVE Online this is going to be familar to you.The ships move similarly like EVE Online's propulsion physics, meaning there's no Newtonian mechanics here. You coast to a stop after you end propulsion, of which there are two, RCS thrusters and main engine. In this game you move directionally using the W A S and D key and laterally using Q and E. Ships use a form of fuel which is converted to energy that is then used to power weapons, defense systems, gadgets and so on.The game may crash in singleplayer mode from time to time but because it autosaves when you go from system to system, or dock, it's not a big inconvienence.Recommendation? This is a beautifully visual game where every control and menu makes sense being where they should be. It does not require a killer graphics card and even old laptops can play it with the tweaking of the graphics controls. Buy it. It's a fun space romp in a desolate galaxy where anything can happen."
