76561198061823625,Recommended,324260,35481787,Posted: 4 October,all,Saffron,"So I'm flying around my newbie ship in the starting system having a pretty good time with the game. I did the opening quests, rescued a few survivors, killed some pirate lieutenants, and mined a LOT of asteroids. You can never have too much money when you first start a game.After mining, I loaded up on all the best kit available at the starting station -- whichi sn't very much. I put a light laser and autocannon on my ship, bought a new engine that even the item's description said was a bad engine, but it was still better than the civilian engine I was currently using. The rest of the kit I had on my ship was the stuff you start the game with. There just wasn't anything else to buy.Now I choose to locate the Order faction recruiter who was located 3 jumps away. No problem. I make the jump to the first system right next door to the starting system -- and I'm immediately destroyed by a swarm of pirates. Yeah,  it's the standard jump gate ambush tactic that I really loathe.  By the time you've even oriented on the change of scenery and figured out which ship is actually yours, you're dead.I tried just letting autopilot take me through the swarm on cruise -- but that doesn't work, either. First, there's usually a collision or two, slowing your ship down to a crawl. If you manage to get through that, the range on the pirate's weapons reaches halfway across the system, so you're still getting pummeled even if you run away.Okay, forget that quest. I'll do it later. So I decide to jump to a different system, a high tech system right next door with a danger rating of 4. Oh good, maybe I can buy better weapons or even a better hull with more hardpoints. How dangerous can a danger rating of 4 be, anyway?I jump through to the high tech system and -- yeah, you guessed it. Another pirate swarm. This time I managed to blow through them but ended up with no shields and only 35% of my structure remaining. I fly for a second or two and ended up in the middle of a second pirate swarm.Because yeah, the pirates seem to know the moment you jump into the system and know exactly where you are. I don't even have time to open up my map to plot a course to a station. If I try to do that, I get killed. Again.Hey, I don't want a game to be pathetically easy -- but when you can't even leave the starting system without getting obliterated mere seconds after jumping, that's not a challenge, that's developmental griefing. In essence, you've programmed the AI to mimic the worst kind of behavior of real people.And I don't have any options. It's not like this happened mid-game and I have a bad spec or a lousy ship. It's not like I can improve my ship in any way, either, since the only station accessible is the station you start in.I really should give this game a thumbs down. I really should. I hate griefers so much that I stopped playing multiplayer games altogether -- there's no sportsmanship, no sense of honor. Games are so stupidly competitive now that bad behavior is just part of the so-called ""fun.""So when the AI is actually programmed to mimic griefers ambushing you at the jump gate ... reminds me of EVE Online , well, I should give it a bad review.And no, I don't want to hear anyone defending multiplayer and how people behave -- and how not everyone is like that, blah blah. Yeah, I know not everyone is like that. But all it takes is a few. No point in calling me names, either, because that would just prove my point, now, wouldn't it.At any rate, I'll still give this game a thumbs up because, aside from the pirate swarms at the jump gates, it's actually a fun little game. It would be nice if the devs toned down the ridiculous pirate swarms -- especially around the jump gates near the starting location -- but I doubt that will ever happen."
